05199nam a22008055i 9780231543897DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016058572  a(OCoLC)984686831  a97802315438977 a10.7312/mart181922doi  a(DE-B1597)480300  a(OCoLC)984512331  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPS374.C596bM37 2017 4aPS374.C596bM37 2019 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a813.6092231 aMartin, Theodore, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aContemporary Drift :bGenre, Historicism, and the Problem of the Present /cTheodore Martin. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b23 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLiterature Now00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Theses on the Concept of the Contemporary -- tChapter One. Decade: Period Pieces -- tChapter Two. Revival: Situating Noir -- tChapter Three. Waiting: Mysterious Circumstances -- tChapter Four. Weather: Western Climes -- tChapter Five. Survival: Work and Plague -- tConclusion: How to Historicize the Present -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat does it mean to call something "contemporary"? More than simply denoting what's new, it speaks to how we come to know the present we're living in and how we develop a shared story about it. The story of trying to understand the present is an integral, yet often unnoticed, part of the literature and film of our moment. In Contemporary Drift, Theodore Martin argues that the contemporary is not just a historical period but also a conceptual problem, and he claims that contemporary genre fiction offers a much-needed resource for resolving that problem.Contemporary Drift combines a theoretical focus on the challenge of conceptualizing the present with a historical account of contemporary literature and film. Emphasizing both the difficulty and the necessity of historicizing the contemporary, the book explores how recent works of fiction depict life in an age of global capitalism, postindustrialism, and climate change. Through new histories of the novel of manners, film noir, the Western, detective fiction, and the postapocalyptic novel, Martin shows how the problem of the contemporary preoccupies a wide range of novelists and filmmakers, including Zadie Smith, Colson Whitehead, Vikram Chandra, China Miéville, Kelly Reichardt, and the Coen brothers. Martin argues that genre provides these artists with a formal strategy for understanding both the content and the concept of the contemporary. Genre writing, with its mix of old and new, brings to light the complicated process by which we make sense of our present and determine what belongs to our time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican fictiony21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aContemporary, The, in literature. 0aContemporary, The, in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311054330808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2017z9783110548198oZDB-23-DKU40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/mart1819240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231543897423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231543897/original